text: Well, I appreciate you getting us back on the highway there of the main thread. And it's a really interesting topic that you bring up. This is your edge in your computational power or is your edge in your data? And to your point, in the era post-2008, the number of free open source computational tools, the ability to quickly churn through that data has really gone exponential. I mean, in the Python landscape, you mentioned pandas, but things like scikit-learn and TensorFlow and all this stuff all of a sudden make machine learning techniques one line of code and makes it that much easier to just sort of throw a handful of variables in a blender and hope something good comes out. So that's something we definitely want to return to. But back to sort of the main thread about replication and a little bit of the history here, because I do find it interesting. It was in 2008 that Andrew Lowe first published sort of the seminal work, I guess you could call it, on hedge fund replication. And if memory serves me correctly, it was a pretty... simplistic model. It was, I think, just using 36 months of prior returns and doing a very simple linear regression with some liquid factors. He showed you could get some pretty meaningful replication. And the idea caught on pretty quickly. You mentioned a little bit in your first answer the zeitgeist of the 2008 era. But you saw this idea really took hold. I know that some banks started issuing products. They were selling products privately that were actual implementations of Andrew's idea. Can you tell us a little bit more about from your perspective working at the fund to hedge funds, what things were like in the evaluation of the hedge fund community, what the attitude was towards hedge funds and maybe why these replicators were becoming to be so attractive to investors?
